Training Paces
 
Below is a listing of the most effective training paces for your level of fitness. To find your point level, go to the Race Times page and find your most recent race or time trial time that you think most accurately reflects your current fitness. That is your starting point point level for your workout paces.  Next find the point level for your goal race time, that is where you will want to gradually get your training paces to over the course of the training cycle. 

Important Note: Training paces are a guide only. The first focus of a run should be the approriate/desired effort level and good execution of the purpose of the workout, and paces used as a sanity check and for measurement and feedback purposes. Paces may also need to be adjusted for weather and course conditions.
The Training Pace charts below are organized by runner type and shown both for pace per mile and pace per kilometer.
If you are unsure as to your running type use the Neutral Runner charts.

- Neutral Runners - fares equally as well against peers at most distance - 70-80% of runners
- Aerobic Monsters - excels at longer races and long workouts but struggles with speedwork and short races - 10-15% of runners
- Speed Demons - excels at shorter races and speed work but struggles at longer races and long runs - 10-15% of runners
